elements.content: Reaction of ligands, 1,6-di(triazole-1-yl-methyl)-4-R-phenol [dttp (R = t-Bu), dtmp (R = Me), dtcp (R = Cl)], with Cd(SCN)2 leads to the formation of various coordination polymers with different structures. Coordination polymer [Cd(dttp)2(SCN)2] (1) possesses a one-dimensional (1D) looped chain running along the c-axis, while isostructural polymers [Cd(dtmp)(SCN)2·CH3OH] (2) and [Cd(dtcp)(SCN)2·CH3OH] (3) feature a novel 1D tube-like chain running along the a-axis. Distinct assemblies are observed in 1, 2, and 3 due to the spatial hindrance of different substituted groups bonded to the phenol rings. In contrast, 1,6-di(triazole-1-yl-methyl)-4-chlorophenol (dtcp) with Cd(SCN)2 under a solvothermal reaction condition yields a remarkable and unique three-dimensional (3D) polymer [Cd(dtcp)(SCN)2] (4).

Introduction

The current interest in the crystal engineering of metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) stems not only from their potential applications as functional materials, but also from their intriguing variety of architectures and molecular topologies. Generally, factors that influence the final assembly are numerous, inclusive of the coordination configuration of metal ions involved, the geometric characteristics of organic ligands as spacers, metal-ligand ratios, solvents, the feature of counter-anions, the reaction conditions and so forth. At present, the construction of desirable MOFs is often realized by discreet selection of metal ions, counter-anions, and organic ligands.

elements.content: Recently, a number of diazole ligands have been studied for molecular assembly, treatment of these ligands with first-row transition metal salts (Mn(II), Fe(II), Co(II), Ni(II), Cu(II), and Zn(II)) usually leads to the formation of one-dimensional (1D) chains containing 24-membered M2L2 macrocycles or two-dimensional (2D) layered structures with rhombohedral grid units of 48-membered M4L4 metallocycles. We have also designed and prepared a number of diazole containing ligands, one of which is illustrated in Scheme . Assembly of these ligands with some transition metal ions (Cu(II), Zn(II), Fe(II), Co(II), Ni(II), Mn(II)) resulted in a variety of coordination polymers with distinc architectures. To expand our system and to explore the effect of noncoordinated groups on self-assembly, we prefer to use cadmium(II) ions which are much bigger and suitable for a fixed octahedral configuration of coordination. Since thioncyanate anions can act as either a bridging ligand or a terminal coligand, this counteranion is expected to have significant impacts on the structure of complexes. Thus, Cd(SCN)2 is chosen as a metal source to assemble with our triazole ligands. Herein reported is an orientated assembly example by adjusting noncoordinated groups in the ligand while treated with Cd(SCN)2.

X-ray Crystallography

Single-crystal X-ray diffraction data were measured on a Siemens SMART CCD diffractometer using graphite-monochromatic Mo Kαradiation (λ = 0.71073 Å). Data collection was performed with using SMART program. Cell refinement and data reduction were made with the SAINT program. Structures were solved by direct methods and refined on F 2 by using full-matrix least-squares methods with SHELXTL version 6.10.

Results and DiscussionDescription of Crystal Structures. [Cd(dttp)<sub>2</sub>(SCN)<sub>2</sub>] (<bold>1</bold>)

Reaction of dttp with Cd(SCN)2 produced a coordination polymer 1 in which [2 + 2] metallomacrocycles are connected side by side to form a 1D looped chain. The X-ray structure analysis shows that compound 1 crystallizes in the triclinic space group P−1 with half of one Cd(II) atom, one dttp ligand, and one thiocyanate ion in an asymmetric unit. Each metal atom is located on a symmetry center with a hexa-coordinated octahedral geometry, formed equatorially by four nitrogen atoms of trizoles from four dttp ligands and axially by two nitrogen atoms from two thiocyanate anions. The thiocyanate anion here acts as a monodentate N-bound ligand with an end-on coordination mode. Each dttp functions as a bridging ligand through two triazole moieties to link two metal atoms to form a 24-membered ring with a unit of [Cd2(dttp)2], and the Cd···Cd separation across the bridging dttp is 11.350 Å. The macrocyclic units repeating along the c-axis via metal knots lead to the generation of a 1D looped chain with NCS– groups on terminal positions shown in Figure . It is noted that each dttp adopts a cis conformation and the dihedral angle between the mean planes of the two triazole-rings inside a dttp is equal to 76.5°.

elements.content: Substitution of dtmp for dttp in our next test with Cd(SCN)2, however, yielded a new coordination polymer 2 whose assembly mode was drastically different from that of 1 (Figure ). The asymmetric unit of 2 consists of one Cd(II) atom, one dtmp ligand, two thiocyanate ions and one methanol molecule. Each Cd(II) atom is also in a slightly distorted octahedral arrangement with four nitrogen atoms consisting of the basal plane. Dissimilar to 1, two N atoms are from two dtmp ligands and the other two are from two thiocyanate groups, and two sulfur atoms of two thiocyanate anions occupy the axial positions completing the octahedral coordination. A 24-membered M2L2 macrocyclic ring through Cd−N coordination bonds was also formed, in which both dtmps are in a cis conformation as well. The intermetallic distance within a macrocycle is 7.494 Å, conspicuously shorter than that in 1, because the ligand in complex 2 distorts more seriously than that in complex 1. The dihedral angle between the mean planes of the two triazole-rings inside a dtmp is equal to 119.2°. It is of much interest to observe that metallomacrocycles here are connected via metal knots in a face-to-face mode to form a 1D tube-like chain made up of M2L2 ring units and double-stranded chain of [Cd(SCN)2]∞, in which Cd(II) ions from the neighboring metallomacrocycles are bridged by two thiocyanate groups in a μ2 end-to-end mode (Figure ). Two antiparallel thiocyanate ligands with two metal atoms form an 8-membered [Cd2(SCN)2] parallelogram with edge lengths of 2.77 and 4.69 Å, and angles of 85.6 and 94.4°, respectively. The corresponding Cd−N−C bonds are almost linear [Cd1−N7−C14, 164.6°; Cd1−N8−C15, 165.8°], whereas the Cd−S−C linkages are rather bent [Cd1−S1−C14, 100.6°; Cd1−S2−C15, 98.4°]. The Cd···Cd distance across the bridging thiocyanate anions is 5.036 Å.

elements.content: It is found that there exists a large channel formed by superposition of the M2L2 rings with a unit of Cd2(dtmp)2 if the tube is viewed from the a-axis. Methanol molecules are located inside the channel by means of multiple hydrogen bonding interactions. Among them, one phenolic hydroxy group inside the cavity interacts with a methanol molecule through O−H···O hydrogen bonding [O1−H1A···O2, 1.91 Å], and SCN– anions further strengthen the interaction with methanol molecules by O−H···S hydrogen bonding interactions (O2−H2A···S2, 2.83 Å). In addition, the role of C−H···O interactions between the carbon atom of triazole and the oxygen atom of methanol cannot be ignored in encapsulating the methanol molecules (C9−H9···O2, 2.39 Å). It is noticed that the 1D tube with large inner channels extends in a parallel arrangement in the bc-plane to form a 3D framework by π−π interactions (Figure ). The π−π interactions between two adjacent tubes by overlapping their triazole rings along both b and c directions are at interlayer distances of 3.788 and 3.421 Å, respectively.

elements.content: Considering the comparable sizes of a chlorine atom and a methyl group, one may expect that treatment of dtcp with Cd(SCN)2 would give an analogous coordination polymer to 2. Crystallographic results reveal that 3 also has a 1D tube-like structural motif with 24-membered Cd2(dtcp)2 macrocyclic rings connected by by [Cd(SCN)2] units. The distances of two cadmium atoms via dtcp and SCN–bridges are 7.464 and 5.970 Å, respectively. Although 2 and 3 have similar molecular structures, they present different packing in their crystals due to the difference of the substituted groups in the ligand backbone (Figure ). A remarkable feature of 3 is that there are S…Cl interactions involved in the stabilization of crystal lattice, which are presented in limited structures. Adjacent ladders running along b-axis are linked by the intermolecular S…Cl contact between S1 and Cl1 with a distance of 3.510 Å that is smaller than the corresponding van der Waals radii sum of 3.75 Å. Thus the 1D tube is further linked to a 3D framework by S···Cl interactions together with π−π interactions of adjacent triazole rings like 2.

elements.content: The most fascinating structural feature of 4 is that each thiocyanate group in a μ2 mode links two Cd centers, resulting in the formation of a 2D neutral layer structure in the bc-plane (Figure ). Among them, two antiparallel μ2 thiocyanate ligands with two metal atoms form a 8-membered Cd2(SCN)2pseudohexagon. In each Hexagen, the corresponding S−N−C bonds are almost linear [N7−C13−S1, 178.8°], whereas the Cd−S−C and Cd−N−C linkages are rather bent [Cd1−S1−C13, 96.76°; Cd1−N7−C13, 143.3°], which are different from 2 and 3. The hexagon lies in a chair form that is much like a cyclohexyl ring as shown in Figure . The two Cd atoms within each [Cd2(NCS)2] dimer are separated by 5.686 Å. The dimers are further linked by four additional SCN– groups to other dimers to form a 2D inorganic structure. The average Cd···Cd distance bridged by the linkage SCN– ligands is 5.942 Å. It is best to be described as a two-dimensional inorganic layer of neutral cadmium thiocyanate complex, which has been observed in [Cd(dmen)(SCN) 2 ] n . Such inorganic layers are arranged in an ···ABAB··· sequence along the a-axis, and further linked together by bridging dtcp ligands through Cd−N coordination bonds to give a 3D inorganic–organic hybrid network as shown in Figure . The neighboring Cd···Cd distance across the bridging dtcp ligand is 14.381 Å. Here, each dttp adopts a trans conformation with a dihedral angle of two triazole planes of 140.9°.

elements.content: In summary, we have successfully prepared four novel coordination polymers based on the self-assembly of 1,6-di(triazole-1-yl-methyl)-4-R-phenol (R = t-Bu, Me, or Cl) with cadmium(II) and thiocyanate ions in methanol. Reaction of dttp with Cd(SCN)2 at room temperature generates a 1D looped chain, while interactions of dtmp or dtcp with Cd(SCN)2 give a 1D tube-like chain. The solvothermal reaction of dtcp with Cd(SCN)2 yields an unprecedented 3D coordination polymer. The results show that the size of noncoordinated substituents in our ligands plays a significant role in their assemblies with metal salts. Minor variation of the ligand may result in a complete change of structural motifs. Furthermore, the reaction conditions, the coordination modes of SCN– ions and the geometry of organic ligands provide opportunities for the construction with novel structure and topology.

Reaction of dttp with Cd(SCN)2 at room temperature generates a 1D looped chain, while interactions of dtmp or dtcp with Cd(SCN)2 give a 1D tube-like chain. The solvothermal reaction of dtcp with Cd(SCN)2 yields an unprecedented 3D coordination polymer. The results show that the size of noncoordinated substituents in our ligands plays a significant role in their assemblies with metal salts. Minor variation of the ligand may result in a complete change of structural motifs. Furthermore, the reaction conditions, the coordination modes of SCN- ions and the geometry of organic ligands provide opportunities for the construction with novel structure and topology.
